  "prompt": "How is gender determined genetically?",
  "response": "Gender, or more accurately, biological sex, is determined genetically in humans primarily through the **sex chromosomes** inherited from parents. Here's how it works:\n\n1. **Sex Chromosomes**:  \n   - Humans have 23 pairs of chromosomes, one of which is the pair of sex chromosomes (X and Y).  \n   - Females typically have two X chromosomes (XX).  \n   - Males typically have one X and one Y chromosome (XY).\n\n2. **Inheritance**:  \n   - A person inherits one sex chromosome from each parent.  \n   - The mother always contributes an X chromosome (since females have XX).  \n   - The father can contribute either an X or a Y chromosome (since males have XY).  \n   - If the father contributes an X, the offspring will be female (XX).  \n   - If the father contributes a Y, the offspring will be male (XY).\n\n3. **The SRY Gene**:  \n   - The Y chromosome contains a gene called the **SRY (Sex-determining Region Y)** gene.  \n   - The SRY gene initiates the development of male characteristics by triggering the formation of testes during embryonic development.  \n   - In the absence of the SRY gene (i.e., in XX individuals), ovaries develop, leading to female characteristics.\n\n4. **Other Genetic Factors**:  \n   - While the SRY gene is the primary determinant of biological sex, other genes on the X and Y chromosomes also influence sexual development.  \n   - In rare cases, mutations or chromosomal abnormalities (e.g., XXY, XYY, or Turner syndrome XO) can result in variations in sex development.\n\nIn summary, genetic sex is determined by the combination of sex chromosomes (XX or XY) and the presence or absence of the SRY gene, which directs the development of male or female biological traits.",
